article.description: Detroit won just nine games last season, but has officially gone from worst to first after clinching the WNBA's best record on Saturday.
article.headline: Detroit marks turnaround from last year
article.linkText: OT win gives Detroit best record, home court in playoffs
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Rookie Nicole Ohlde scored 12 points to help
lift the Minnesota Lynx past the Detroit Shock 74-65 in an
exhibition game Tuesday afternoon.

The 6-foot-4 center from Kansas State opened the game with two
low-post baskets, then started the second half by making a pair of
long jumpers to give Minnesota a 14-point lead.

Tamika Williams added 12 points for the Lynx, and Merlakia Jones
led the defending WNBA champion Detroit with 16 points on 6-of-8
shooting. The Shock were missing leading rebounder Cheryl Ford, who
is out with a lower back strain.
